hip. Delving into works by Mark Twain, Henry James, William Dean Howells, and others, Nissen identifies the genre’s unique features and explores the connections between romantic friendships in literature and in real life. Situating love between men at the heart of Victorian culture, Nissen radically alters our understanding of the American literary canon. And with its deep insights into the emotional and intellectual life of the period, Manly Love also offers a fresh perspective on nineteenth-century America’s attitudes toward love, friendship, marriage, and sex.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAmerican fictionxHistory and criticismx19th century. 0aAmerican fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMale friendship in literature. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aliterature, friendship, romance, homosexuality, homosociality, masculinity, love, affection, relationships, passion, men, marriage, sex, sexuality, william dean howells, henry james, mark twain, cecil dreeme, gender, roderick hudson, domesticity, gilded age, victorian, saloonkeepers daughter, belonging, huckleberry finn, tramp, mobility, home, homeless, hazard of new fortunes, homofiliation, nonfiction.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226586687423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226586687/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles